B.a6a=new A.fq("Metabolic","Diabetes Mellitus is the undisputed most common cause of peripheral neuropathy worldwide.")
B.a69=new A.fq("Autoimmune","The immune system attacks the nerve myelin (e.g., Guillain-Barr\xe9 Syndrome, CIDP).")
B.a6f=new A.fq("Toxic / Nutritional","Chemotherapy agents, Vitamin B12 deficiency, heavy metal poisoning.")
B.a6m=new A.fq("Focal Compression","Nerves trapped and crushed in tight anatomical spaces (e.g., Carpal Tunnel Syndrome, Ulnar Neuropathy at the elbow).")
B.ayh=s([B.a6a,B.a69,B.a6f,B.a6m],t.RY)
B.a6d=new A.fq("Distal Weakness","Weakness begins at the absolute furthest points: the toes, feet, and hands. Frequent tripping, foot drop, or dropping coffee mugs.")
B.a6c=new A.fq("Stocking-Glove Sensory Loss","Numbness, burning, and tingling marching slowly up from the toes and fingers toward the trunk.")
B.a6i=new A.fq("Reduced Reflexes","Deep tendon reflexes (like the ankle jerk) are diminished or completely absent early in the disease course.")
B.a68=new A.fq("Length-Dependent","The longest nerves in the body (running from the lower back all the way down to the toes) succumb to metabolic stress first.")
B.a1p=s([B.a6d,B.a6c,B.a6i,B.a68],t.RY)
B.a_r=s(["Decreased Amplitude: Wallerian degeneration physically severs the axons. Fewer surviving axons means less electricity hits the muscle, resulting in a dropped motor CMAP or a dropped sensory SNAP.","Normal Conduction Velocity: The few axons that survived the attack still have their pristine myelin insulation. They conduct at a perfectly normal speed. The signal just lacks total power.","Normal Latency: The signal arrives exactly when expected."],t.s)
B.aym=new A.yp("The Axonal Pattern",B.a_r)
B.YS=s(["Decreased Velocity: The myelin insulation is destroyed. The electrical signal leaks out and travels sluggishly along the bare axon, plummeting the conduction velocity (<75% of normal).","Increased Latency: Because the signal is moving so slowly, it takes much longer to arrive at the recording electrode.","Conduction Block: If the demyelination is severe enough at a focal spot, the signal completely drops across that segment."],t.s)
B.ayl=new A.yp("The Demyelinating Pattern",B.YS)
B.a_3=s(["Giant MUAPs: When a motor nerve dies, the muscle fibers it controlled become 'orphans'. A neighboring healthy nerve will sprout new branches and adopt these orphans. Now, one nerve controls twice as many muscle fibers. When it fires, it produces an abnormally massive (Giant) electrical wave.","Long Duration MUAPs: Because the single nerve is trying to synchronize the firing of a huge, sprawled-out territory of adopted muscle fibers, the electrical wave stretches out in time.","Reduced Recruitment (Fast Firing): Because so many nerves have died, the brain has very few motor units left to recruit. If you ask the patient to lift a heavy weight, the few surviving giant units fire incredibly fast to compensate, but they simply cannot fill the screen with activity.","Spontaneous Activity: If you put the needle in a resting muscle and hear 'rain on a tin roof' (Fibrillations and Positive Sharp Waves), you are hearing the desperate cries of actively orphaned muscle fibers looking for a nerve supply."],t.s)
B.a6L=new A.Ud("What is Neuropathy?","Neuropathy refers to disorders affecting the peripheral nerves (the 'wiring'). The muscles themselves are structurally capable, but the electrical cables carrying instructions from the spinal cord to the muscles (motor nerves) or from the skin back to the brain (sensory nerves) are damaged. Peripheral nerve damage generally falls into two distinct biometric patterns: Axonal Loss (the wire breaks) or Demyelination (the insulation strips away).",B.a1p,"Classic Needle EMG Findings (Chronic Reinnervation)",null,null,B.a_3)
B.a6h=new A.fq("Inflammatory","The immune system inappropriately attacks the muscle tissue (e.g., Polymyositis, Dermatomyositis).")
B.a6g=new A.fq("Metabolic / Endocrine","Systemic imbalances disrupting muscle function (e.g., severe Hypothyroidism, chronic steroid use).")
B.a6k=new A.fq("Genetic (Dystrophies)","Inherited mutations causing structural defects in the muscle wall proteins (e.g., Duchenne, Becker, Facioscapulohumeral).")
B.a6e=new A.fq("Toxic","Medication or substance-induced muscle damage (e.g., Statin-induced myopathy, severe chronic alcohol abuse).")
B.ayg=s([B.a6h,B.a6g,B.a6k,B.a6e],t.RY)
B.a6l=new A.fq("Proximal Weakness","Difficulty raising arms above the head, combing hair, getting up from a low chair, or climbing stairs. The large proximal muscles (deltoids, hip flexors) usually fail first.")
B.a6j=new A.fq("Symmetric Involvement","Strength loss typically affects the left and right sides of the body equally.")
B.a67=new A.fq("Purely Motor","Sensory nerves are entirely unaffected. There is NO numbness, tingling, or loss of sensation.")
B.a6b=new A.fq("Muscle Pain","Often present, especially if the myopathy is inflammatory or necrotizing in nature.")
B.a20=s([B.a6l,B.a6j,B.a67,B.a6b],t.RY)
B.a0w=s(["Short Duration: A normal motor unit contains hundreds of healthy muscle fibers. In a myopathy, the nerve is fine, but many of its target muscle fibers have died or shriveled. When the nerve fires, fewer fibers respond, causing the electrical wave to be physically shorter in time.","Small Amplitude: Because fewer fibers are generating voltage within the unit, the overall electrical output (height) drops.","Polyphasic: The surviving muscle fibers are sick and regenerating. They do not fire together in perfect sync. This asynchronous firing creates a jagged, multi-peaked wave (>5 phases) instead of a clean spike."],t.s)
B.a6N=new A.yp("The Motor Unit Action Potential (MUAP)",B.a0w)
B.YA=s(["Early / Rapid Recruitment: This is the hallmark of myopathy. Because each individual motor unit is terribly weak, the brain realizes it cannot generate force normally. If you ask the patient to lightly lift a finger, the brain panics and instantly recruits almost every available motor unit to compensate. The screen fills with chaotic electrical activity despite the patient barely exerting any effort.","Full Interference Pattern: Even at minimal effort, the screen is entirely full of firing units.","Low Amplitude: Despite the screen being completely full, the overall height of the 'cloud' of activity remains short, because all the units are tiny and sick."],t.s)
B.a6O=new A.yp("The Recruitment Pattern",B.YA)
B.a6M=new A.Ud("What is Myopathy?","Myopathy refers to diseases of the muscle tissue where the primary pathology directly attacks the muscle fibers. The nerves controlling these muscles are entirely healthy, but the 'engine' they are trying to drive is fundamentally broken. Whether the muscle is structurally defective (dystrophy), under inflammatory attack (myositis), or chemically poisoned (toxins), the end result is a severely weakened electrical generator.",B.a20,"Classic Needle EMG Findings",B.a6N,B.a6O,null)
B.a71=new A.FY(null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null)
