B.ZD=s(["Upper Trunk","Lateral Cord","C6 Nerve Root","Median Nerve at the wrist"],t.s)
B.aaI=new A.bx("A patient presents with numbness in the thumb and index finger (C6 distribution). The Median SNAP (recording Digit 2) is normal. Where is the most likely location of the lesion?",B.ZD,2,"If the SNAP is NORMAL in a region of numbness, the lesion is PRE-GANGLIONIC (a nerve root). Post-ganglionic lesions (Plexus/Nerve) destroy the sensory axons distal to the DRG, causing a drop in SNAP amplitude.")
B.Zy=s(["Lower Trunk Brachial Plexopathy","C8/T1 Nerve Root Avulsion","Ulnar Neuropathy at the Cubital Tunnel","Neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome"],t.s)
B.ab2=new A.bx("A patient presents with a 'Claw Hand' and severe hand intrinsic weakness. You also note Miosis and Ptosis on the same side (Horner's Syndrome). This strongly localizes to:",B.Zy,1,"Horner's Syndrome + C8/T1 symptoms indicates a PRE-GANGLIONIC (root) lesion high enough to involve the sympathetic rami. This usually suggests a traumatic pre-ganglionic root avulsion.")
B.a19=s(["Supraspinatus","Deltoid","Rhomboids (Dorsal Scapular Nerve)","Biceps"],t.s)
B.aaG=new A.bx("Which muscle is supplied by a branch directly off the C5 root, making it a critical 'Root vs. Trunk' discriminator on EMG?",B.a19,2,"The Rhomboids are innervated by the Dorsal Scapular Nerve, which branches directly off the C5 ROOT. If Rhomboids are spared but the Supraspinatus (Upper Trunk) is weak, the lesion must be at the Trunk level.")
B.a2l=s(["Pancoast Tumor",u.i,"Acute C5 Radiculopathy","Axillary Nerve Entrapment"],t.s)
B.ab1=new A.bx("A patient presents with sudden, intense, 'unbearable' shoulder pain that lasts for a week, followed by progressive weakness in the shoulder and serratus anterior. This is characteristic of:",B.a2l,1,"Sudden severe pain followed by multi-focal weakness (often including the Long Thoracic Nerve causing winging) is the hallmark of Parsonage-Turner Syndrome.")
B.YG=s(["Upper Trunk; Median SNAP drop","Lower Trunk; Median CMAP drop + Ulnar SNAP drop","Cords; Normal SNAPs","Roots; Fasciculations"],t.s)
B.aaK=new A.bx("Neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome (nTOS) classically affects which part of the plexus and leads to which EMG finding?",B.YG,1,"nTOS (Gilliatt-Sumner hand) involves the Lower Trunk. It is unique because it shows a Median CMAP drop (loss of thenar fibers) and an Ulnar SNAP drop (loss of T1/C8 sensory fibers).")
B.a2t=s(["Lateral Cord","Medial Cord","Posterior Cord","Terminal Cord"],t.s)
B.abc=new A.bx("Which cord of the brachial plexus is formed solely by the combination of the posterior divisions of all three trunks?",B.a2t,2,"The Posterior Cord is unique as it receives input from all three trunks (Upper, Middle, and Lower) via their posterior divisions.")
B.a_X=s(["C8-T1; Claw Hand","C5-C6; Waiter's Tip","C7; Wrist Drop","C5-T1; Flail Arm"],t.s)
B.aaS=new A.bx("An 'Erb's Palsy' typically involves which roots and results in what classic limb posture?",B.a_X,1,"Erb's palsy involves the Upper Trunk (C5-C6). Loss of abductors and external rotators results in the arm being adducted and internally rotated (Waiter's Tip).")
B.a_2=s(["Abductor Pollicis Brevis","First Dorsal Interosseous","Biceps Brachii","Extensor Indicis Proprius"],t.s)
B.aaQ=new A.bx("During reinnervation after a severe global plexus injury, which of these muscles will show recovery FIRST?",B.a_2,2,"Nerves regrow at ~1mm/day. Muscles closest to the plexus (proximal, like the Biceps) will receive axons and show recovery long before distal hand muscles.")
B.a1f=s(["Radial Nerve","Axillary Nerve","Musculocutaneous Nerve","Thoracodorsal Nerve"],t.s)
B.abl=new A.bx("A lesion strictly localized to the Posterior Cord would spare which of these nerves?",B.a1f,2,"The Musculocutaneous nerve originates from the Lateral Cord. The Posterior Cord gives rise to the Radial, Axillary, Subscapular, and Thoracodorsal nerves.")
B.a0y=s(["Medial Cord / Lower Trunk","Lateral Cord","C6 Radiculopathy","Ulnar nerve at the elbow"],t.s)
B.abt=new A.bx("You find low SNAPs in the Medial Antebrachial Cutaneous (MAC) and Ulnar distributions, but a normal Median SNAP (Digit 2). This geographic pattern localizes to:",B.a0y,0,"MAC and Ulnar SNAPs both represent the C8-T1/Medial Cord/Lower Trunk pathway. Sparing of the Median SNAP (C6-C7/Lateral Cord) confirms the geographic boundary.")
B.ZN=s(["FDI (Ulnar)","APB (Median)","ADM (Ulnar)","EIP (Radial)"],t.s)
B.abg=new A.bx("What is the primary recording site for motor NCS in a suspected case of neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome?",B.ZN,1,"While nTOS is a lower trunk/medial cord issue, the fibers to the APB (Median) are often more selectively lost, leading to the characteristic thenar atrophy (Gilliatt-Sumner hand).")
B.a0A=s([B.aaI,B.ab2,B.aaG,B.ab1,B.aaK,B.abc,B.aaS,B.aaQ,B.abl,B.abt,B.abg],t.hB)
B.abz=new A.lY(B.a0A,"Geographic Mastery","Prove your ability to localize complex brachial plexus lesions.",null)
B.a_i=s(["Abductor Pollicis Brevis (APB)","First Dorsal Interosseous (FDI)","Opponens Pollicis","Flexor Carpi Ulnaris"],t.s)
B.ab6=new A.bx("Which muscle is the most distal innervated by the Ulnar nerve and is essential for evaluating Froment's sign?",B.a_i,1,"The FIRST DORSAL INTEROSSEOUS (FDI) is the most distal muscle innervated by the ulnar nerve. Weakness here results in Froment's sign, where the patient must substitute the median-innervated FPL for pinching. Sampling FDI is mandatory to differentiate ulnar entrapment at Guyon's canal from lower radiculopathies.")
B.Zd=s(["Sampling the Adductor Pollicis","Overshooting into the Opponens Pollicis","Hitting the Radial Artery","Entering the Flexor Pollicis Longus"],t.s)
B.abu=new A.bx("When sampling the Abductor Pollicis Brevis (APB), what is a common technical pitfall if the needle is inserted too deeply?",B.Zd,1,"If you insert the needle too deeply (beyond 1/2 inch) in the thenar eminence, you will overshoot the superficial APB and inadvertently sample the deeper OPPONENS POLLICIS muscle. Precise shallow depth is required for APB.")
B.XC=s(["Extensor Digitorum Communis","Extensor Indicis Proprius (EIP)","Brachioradialis","Extensor Carpi Radialis Longus"],t.s)
B.aaM=new A.bx("Which muscle is the 'ultimate test' to rule out a distal radial nerve injury, such as Posterior Interosseous Nerve (PIN) entrapment at the Arcade of Frohse?",B.XC,1,"The EXTENSOR INDICIS PROPRIUS (EIP) is usually the most distal muscle innervated by the radial nerve complex. It is the definitive muscle to evaluate when ruling out distal PIN entrapment or Saturday night palsy.")
B.a0q=s(["Flexor Digitorum Superficialis","Pronator Teres (PT)","Flexor Carpi Radialis","Palmaris Longus"],t.s)
B.abx=new A.bx("To differentiate a high Median nerve injury from Carpal Tunnel Syndrome, which proximal forearm muscle should be sampled?",B.a0q,1,"The PRONATOR TERES (PT) is the most proximal forearm muscle innervated by the median nerve. Because the nerve passes through its two heads, sampling it helps localize entrapment (Pronator Teres Syndrome) vs distal wrist entrapment.")
B.Zp=s(["Long Head","Medial Head","Lateral Head","All are equally safe"],t.s)
B.aaO=new A.bx("In cases of a suspected C7 radiculopathy, which head of the triceps is generally considered the safest and easiest to sample?",B.Zp,2,"The LATERAL HEAD of the triceps is preferred for routine evaluation. It is critical for C7 isolation; its innervation branches so high in the axilla that it is spared in 'Saturday night palsy' radial nerve compressions at the spiral groove.")
B.ZT=s(["Tibialis Anterior","Extensor Hallucis Longus (EHL)","Peroneus Longus","Gastrocnemius"],t.s)
B.ab_=new A.bx("Which muscle allows for clear differentiation between an L5 radiculopathy and an isolated Peroneal (Fibular) neuropathy because of its Strong L5-S1 representation?",B.ZT,1,"While Tibialis Anterior is primarily L4-L5, the EXTENSOR HALLUCIS LONGUS (EHL) has a stronger L5-S1 representation. This makes EHL an excellent target to differentiate L5 radiculopathy from isolated peroneal nerve injury.")
B.Xy=s(["Inability to jump","Foot drop (loss of dorsiflexion)","Inability to wiggle toes","Severe calf cramping"],t.s)
B.abr=new A.bx("What is the hallmark clinical sign of severe denervation in the Tibialis Anterior muscle?",B.Xy,1,"The TIBIALIS ANTERIOR is the king of foot dorsiflexion. Damage to the deep peroneal nerve or L5 root causes 'FOOT DROP', forcing a high-stepping gait to avoid tripping.")
B.XM=s(["Soleus","Flexor Hallucis Longus","Tibialis Posterior","Medial Gastrocnemius"],t.s)
B.aaX=new A.bx("Which muscle is the deepest and most difficult to reach in the posterior leg compartment, but is critical for evaluating L5 root integrity via the Tibial nerve?",B.XM,2,"The TIBIALIS POSTERIOR is the deepest muscle in the posterior compartment. It is heavily innervated by the L5 root via the Tibial nerve, making it a key discriminator for complex lumbosacral plexopathies.")
B.a1K=s(["Hitting the Sural nerve","Injury to the Posterior Tibial Artery/Nerve bundle","Damaging the Achilles tendon","Overshooting into the Fibula"],t.s)
B.ab7=new A.bx("What is the primary danger when attempting to sample the Tibialis Posterior muscle?",B.a1K,1,"When sampling Tibialis Posterior, the major neurovascular bundle (POSTERIOR TIBIAL ARTERY and NERVE) lies very close. Clinicians must stay tight to the posterior cortex of the tibia and avoid indiscriminate lateral movements.")
B.a_E=s(["Rectus Femoris","Vastus Medialis","Vastus Lateralis","Biceps Femoris"],t.s)
B.abk=new A.bx("Which muscle is the primary shock absorber/extensor of the knee and is the largest component of the quadriceps?",B.a_E,2,"The VASTUS LATERALIS is the largest of the quadriceps. If the Femoral nerve is damaged, the patient loses the ability to lock their knee in extension, causing life-altering instability during walking.")
B.YZ=s([B.ab6,B.abu,B.aaM,B.abx,B.aaO,B.ab_,B.abr,B.aaX,B.ab7,B.abk],t.hB)
B.abA=new A.lY(B.YZ,"Needle Mastery","Validate your anatomical precision and technical knowledge.",null)
B.Zz=s(["Continuous depolarization along the entire axon membrane","Action potentials 'jump' between nodes of Ranvier, depolarizing only at nodes","Myelin increases the resistance of the axon membrane uniformly","Schwann cells actively conduct the electrical signal"],t.s)
B.abn=new A.bx("What is the primary physiological mechanism underlying saltatory conduction in myelinated nerve fibers?",B.Zz,1,"SALTATORY CONDUCTION occurs when action potentials 'JUMP' between nodes of Ranvier in myelinated fibers. This mechanism: (1) increases conduction velocity 50x compared to unmyelinated fibers, (2) requires depolarization only at nodes rather than continuously, (3) is energy efficient by reducing the membrane area requiring active Na+/K+ pumping. Myelination by Schwann cells insulates internodal segments, concentrating voltage-gated channels at nodes.")
B.a1y=s(["Severe Axonal Loss","A Primary Demyelinating Neuropathy","Complete Nerve Transection"],t.s)
B.aaN=new A.bx("A technician performs an NCS on a patient with icy cold hands from walking outside in the winter. What pattern is this most likely to mimic on the screen?",B.a1y,1,"Cold temperatures decisively slow down nerve conduction velocity and prolong latencies, perfectly mirroring the cardinal signs of demyelination. It also paradoxically increases amplitude.")
B.a_D=s(["The speed of the fastest conducting motor fibers","The number of functioning motor axons","The degree of myelination of the nerve","The distance between stimulation sites"],t.s)
B.ab4=new A.bx("In nerve conduction studies, what does CMAP amplitude primarily reflect?",B.a_D,1,"CMAP AMPLITUDE reflects the NUMBER OF FUNCTIONING MOTOR AXONS. When measured from baseline to negative peak (in millivolts), amplitude indicates how many motor units are contributing to the response. AXONAL LOSS causes amplitude reduction because fewer axons depolarize muscle fibers.")
B.XK=s(["The G1 (Active) electrode is not placed over the true motor endpoint","The patient has a conduction block at the elbow","The stimulus intensity is not supramaximal"],t.s)
B.abh=new A.bx("You stimulate the ulnar nerve at the wrist, but note the initial deflection off the baseline is a sharp positive (downward) dip before going upward. What is the most likely cause?",B.XK,0,"If G1 is off the motor endpoint, it records the approaching electrical wavefront as volume conduction before the muscle fully depolarizes under it, creating an initial positive (downward) dip.")
B.a1w=s(["Stimulation at the maximum tolerable intensity for the patient","Stimulation 20-50% above threshold to ensure all axons depolarize","The highest stimulus intensity the equipment can produce","Stimulation that produces a painful sensation"],t.s)
B.ab8=new A.bx("What is supramaximal stimulation, and why is it necessary in motor NCS?",B.a1w,1,"SUPRAMAXIMAL STIMULATION is 20-50% ABOVE the stimulus intensity that produces maximum CMAP amplitude. This ensures ALL motor axons in the nerve are depolarized. Submaximal stimulation causes errors: (1) underestimates amplitude, (2) overestimates conduction velocity (only fastest fibers activated).")
B.a2g=s(["Unmyelinated C-fibers","A-delta fibers","Large, myelinated A-beta fibers"],t.s)
B.abw=new A.bx("Which of the following fibers are you actually evaluating when performing a standard Sural Sensory Nerve Action Potential (SNAP) study?",B.a2g,2,"Standard EDX machines only have the power to resolve the massive, high-speed A-alpha and A-beta fibers. We are completely blind to small pain fibers (A-delta and C fibers).")
B.Zx=s(["CMAP: baseline-to-peak (mV); SNAP: peak-to-peak (\u03bcV)","CMAP: peak-to-peak (mV); SNAP: baseline-to-peak (\u03bcV)","Both are measured peak-to-peak in the same units","Both are measured baseline-to-peak in the same units"],t.s)
B.abf=new A.bx("What is the key difference in how CMAP amplitude versus SNAP amplitude is measured?",B.Zx,0,"CMAP amplitude is measured BASELINE-TO-NEGATIVE PEAK in millivolts (mV), while SNAP amplitude is measured PEAK-TO-PEAK in microvolts (\u03bcV). This difference exists because SNAPs are small (\u03bcV range) and often triphasic with baseline drift, making peak-to-peak more reliable.")
B.XB=s(["It will be completely absent (0 mV)","It will be perfectly normal","It will have a conduction velocity of 20 m/s"],t.s)
B.aaP=new A.bx("A patient presents 24 hours after an acute knife wound completely severed their median nerve at the elbow. What will the median motor CMAP amplitude look like if you stimulate at the wrist today?",B.XB,1,"Wallerian degeneration takes time. The distal axon segment remains electrically viable and can conduct an impulse for 3-5 days (motor) before the structure begins to physically dissolve.")
B.a0f=s(["25 m/s","40 m/s","50 m/s","64 m/s"],t.s)
B.abs=new A.bx("In conduction velocity calculations, if the wrist latency is 3.2ms, elbow latency is 4.8ms, and distance is 8cm, what is the forearm conduction velocity?",B.a0f,2,"CALCULATION: Distance \xf7 (Latency difference) = 8cm \xf7 (4.8ms - 3.2ms) = 8 \xf7 1.6 = 5.0 cm/ms. To get m/s, multiply by 10 (since 10mm = 1cm). So 5.0 * 10 = 50 m/s. This is normal for a median motor nerve.")
B.Zb=s(["Amplitude must drop >50% with minimal temporal dispersion","Velocity must drop below 75% of normal","Amplitude must increase by 20%"],t.s)
B.ab0=new A.bx("To definitively declare Conduction Block, you stimulate proximally. What must happen to the CMAP response compared to the distal stimulation?",B.Zb,0,"A sudden, massive drop in amplitude across a segment proves the signal hit a focal blockade of demyelination and could not pass. If it spreads out widely instead, that is dispersion, not a true block.")
B.ZR=s(["Demyelinating: reduced amplitude with normal CV; Axonal: slow CV with preserved amplitude","Demyelinating: slow CV with conduction blocks; Axonal: reduced amplitude with normal/mildly slow CV","Both show identical NCS patterns","Demyelinating: absent responses; Axonal: prolonged latencies"],t.s)
B.aaL=new A.bx("What pattern distinguishes demyelinating neuropathy from axonal neuropathy on NCS?",B.ZR,1,"DEMYELINATING pattern: Significantly SLOWED CV (<70% of LLN) and markedly prolonged distal latency. AXONAL pattern: Normal or mildly slow CV but REDUCED AMPLITUDES (<50% of LLN).")
B.a0u=s(["A direct motor response that assesses distal nerve segments","A sensory response that evaluates dorsal root function","A late response traveling antidromically to anterior horn cells then returning orthodromically, assessing entire motor pathway","A reflex response through the dorsal root ganglion"],t.s)
B.abi=new A.bx("What is the F-wave, and what does it assess?",B.a0u,2,"The F-WAVE is a LATE MOTOR RESPONSE that assesses the ENTIRE MOTOR PATHWAY. The signal travels antidromically (backwards) to the anterior horn cell, which 'backfires' and sends a signal back down the axon to the muscle.")
B.ZS=s(["Increased amplitude of the proximal response","Reduced duration of the proximal response","Increased duration and reduced amplitude of the proximal response compared to distal","A complete block of conduction"],t.s)
B.aaU=new A.bx("What is temporal dispersion, and what does it signify?",B.ZS,2,"TEMPORAL DISPERSION is the desynchronization of nerve impulses. It manifests as INCREASED DURATION and REDUCED AMPLITUDE of the proximal CMAP. Significant dispersion suggests acquired demyelination (uneven slowing of different fibers).")
B.a0F=s(["H-reflex is a true reflex arc (sensory afferent, motor efferent); F-wave is purely motor","H-reflex is purely motor; F-wave is a reflex","H-reflex is seen in all nerves; F-wave only in tibial nerve","There is no difference"],t.s)
B.abq=new A.bx("How does the H-reflex differ from the F-wave?",B.a0F,0,"The H-REFLEX is a TRUE REFLEX ARC involving Ia sensory afferents synapsing on alpha motor neurons. It is the electrical equivalent of the ankle jerk reflex. The F-WAVE is NOT a reflex; it is a purely motor antidromic backfiring.")
B.YY=s([B.abn,B.aaN,B.ab4,B.abh,B.ab8,B.abw,B.abf,B.aaP,B.abs,B.ab0,B.aaL,B.abi,B.aaU,B.abq],t.hB)
B.abB=new A.lY(B.YY,"NCS Fundamentals","Validate your mastery of the electrical physics of the human body.",null)
B.a0C=s(["Myasthenia Gravis","Motor Neuron Disease (ALS)","Polymyositis","Myotonic Dystrophy"],t.s)
B.abj=new A.bx("Which clinical diagnosis typically presents on EMG with widespread active denervation, large reinnervation MUAPs, and fasciculations?",B.a0C,1,"Widespread denervation + Reinnervation (Large MUAPs) + Fasciculations is the classic triad for Motor Neuron Disease (ALS).")
B.a2d=s(["Seashell sound","Rain on tin roof","Marching soldiers","Dive bomber"],t.s)
B.aaH=new A.bx("What is the characteristic sound of fibrillation potentials on EMG?",B.a2d,1,"Fibrillations fire regularly at 0.5-10Hz, creating a characteristic 'rain on tin roof' sound.")
B.a2p=s(["Always normal","Only seen in myopathy","Associated with radiation plexopathy or MS","Indicates severe stroke"],t.s)
B.aaT=new A.bx("What is the clinical significance of myokymic discharges?",B.a2p,2,"Myokymic discharges (grouped repetitive MUAP firing) are classic for radiation damage or MS (facial).")
B.a_Q=s(["Endplate: initial negative; Fibrillation: initial positive","Endplate: initial positive; Fibrillation: initial negative","Amplitude size","Firing rate"],t.s)
B.aaJ=new A.bx("How do you distinguish normal endplate spikes from pathologic fibrillations?",B.a_Q,0,"Endplate spikes are negative onset (upward) because they are nerve terminal irritation; Pathologic denervation is positive onset (downward) because it starts at the muscle fiber.")
B.YM=s(["Fasciculations","Complex Repetitive Discharges","Myotonic Discharges","CRPS"],t.s)
B.abd=new A.bx("Which EMG pattern is defined by a 'dive bomber' sound and waxing/waning frequency?",B.YM,2,"Myotonic discharges wax and wane in both frequency and amplitude, creating the 'dive bomber' or 'revving engine' sound.")
B.a0v=s(["Rain on tin roof","Corn popping","Machine gun","Waterfall"],t.s)
B.abo=new A.bx("Fasciculations sound similar to:",B.a0v,1,"Fasciculations are single motor units firing irregularly, sounding like 'popcorn' or 'corn popping'.")
B.a_q=s(["2","3","4","5"],t.s)
B.abm=new A.bx("A 'polyphasic' motor unit potential is defined as having more than how many phases?",B.a_q,2,"A MUAP is polyphasic if it has more than 4 phases (where phases = baseline crossings + 1).")
B.Zs=s(["Reduced (fast firing)","Early (full interference at low force)","Normal","Infinite"],t.s)
B.aba=new A.bx("In a patient with severe myopathy, what recruitment pattern is expected?",B.Zs,1,"In myopathy, since each unit is weak, the CNS activates many more units early to compensate for low force.")
B.a17=s(["0.5-10 Hz","50-100 Hz","150-300 Hz","1000 Hz"],t.s)
B.ab3=new A.bx("Neuromyotonic discharges fire at what frequency range?",B.a17,2,"Neuromyotonic discharges are very high frequency (150-300 Hz) decrementing bursts.")
B.ZW=s(["Fibrillations","Fasciculations","Complex Repetitive Discharges (CRDs)","Myotonia"],t.s)
B.abb=new A.bx("What spontaneous activity pattern sounds like a 'machine-like' motorcycle or motorboat due to its perfect regularity?",B.ZW,2,"CRDs are perfectly regular and start/stop abruptly, sounding like a 'motorcycle' or 'motorboat'.")
B.a_s=s(["Single muscle fiber","A single motor unit","A nerve bundle","A spinal cord segment"],t.s)
B.aaW=new A.bx("Fasciculation potentials represent the spontaneous firing of what structure?",B.a_s,1,"Fasciculations are the spontaneous firing of an entire motor unit, whereas fibrillations are firing of single muscle fibers.")
B.a1N=s([B.abj,B.aaH,B.aaT,B.aaJ,B.abd,B.abo,B.abm,B.aba,B.ab3,B.abb,B.aaW],t.hB)
B.abC=new A.lY(B.a1N,"Pattern Recognition Mastery","Challenge your visual and auditory diagnostic skills.",null)
B.a1T=s(["Carpal Tunnel","Median Nerve at the Elbow","C6 Nerve Root","Brachial Plexus"],t.s)
B.aaR=new A.bx("A patient presents with numbness in the thumb and index finger. The Median SNAP (sensory) is completely normal, but the Biceps and Brachioradialis show denervation. Where is the lesion?",B.a1T,2,"This is a classic C6 radiculopathy. The clue is the NORMAL sensory study (SNAP) despite the numbness\u2014this means the pinch is 'Behind the DRG'. The involvement of both the Biceps and Brachioradialis confirms the level.")
B.a0i=s(["To let the pain subside","To allow enough time for fibrillation potentials to develop in the limbs","Because insurance won't pay for it sooner","To allow the disc to heal on its own"],t.s)
B.abe=new A.bx("Why do we wait at least 3 weeks after a sudden disc herniation before doing a full EMG study?",B.a0i,1,"Wallerian degeneration takes time. It takes approximately 2-3 weeks for the distal parts of the nerve in the limbs to show spontaneous activity (fibrillations) after a proximal injury at the root.")
B.a07=s(["Tibialis Anterior","Extensor Hallucis Longus","Gluteus Medius","Gastroc"],t.s)
B.aby=new A.bx("Which muscle should you check to differentiate an L5 radiculopathy from a Peroneal (Fibular) neuropathy?",B.a07,2,"The Gluteus Medius is innervated by the Superior Gluteal Nerve (L5), which branches off the plexus BEFORE the peroneal nerve forms. If the Glut Med is abnormal, the lesion must be at or proximal to the plexus/root level.")
B.ZG=s(["Spinal stenosis","Degenerative spondylosis","Herniated nucleus pulposus (disc herniation)","Malignancy"],t.s)
B.aaY=new A.bx("What is the most common cause of radiculopathy in a 35-year-old patient?",B.ZG,2,"In patients YOUNGER than 50 years, HERNIATED NUCLEUS PULPOSUS is the most common cause. In patients OLDER than 50, SPINAL STENOSIS becomes more prevalent.")
B.Zk=s(["Achilles reflex","Patellar reflex","Biceps reflex","Medial hamstring reflex"],t.s)
B.abp=new A.bx("Which reflex is associated with L4 radiculopathy?",B.Zk,1,"L4 radiculopathy affects the PATELLAR (knee jerk) reflex. The reflex patterns are: L4 = patellar, L5 = medial hamstring, S1 = Achilles.")
B.Yu=s(["Disc herniation","Spinal stenosis","Inflammatory radiculitis","Athletic injury"],t.s)
B.aaV=new A.bx("A 60-year-old patient presents with progressive back pain and bilateral leg weakness. What is the most likely etiology?",B.Yu,1,"In older patients, spinal stenosis due to degenerative changes is the leading cause, often presenting with bilateral symptoms.")
B.a1S=s(["0-5%","10-30%","50-70%","90-100%"],t.s)
B.ab9=new A.bx("What percentage of radiculopathy cases may have paraspinal abnormalities as the ONLY EMG finding?",B.a1S,1,"Paraspinal abnormalities are found as the sole indicator in 10-30% of cases, making paraspinal examination crucial for root localization.")
B.a13=s(["EMG timeline","Myotomal patterns","Non-mechanical causes","Reflex associations"],t.s)
B.ab5=new A.bx("What does the 'HI MADAM' mnemonic help remember?",B.a13,2,"'HI MADAM' covers non-mechanical causes like Herpes, Inflammatory, Metastasis, Arachnoiditis, Diabetes, Abscess, and Mass.")
B.Z7=s(["C5","C6","C7","C8"],t.s)
B.abv=new A.bx("Which nerve root is most commonly affected in cervical radiculopathy?",B.Z7,2,"C7 is the most commonly affected cervical nerve root (approx 70%), usually presenting with triceps weakness.")
B.a1C=s(["Weakness of ankle dorsiflexion","Loss of patellar reflex","Loss of Achilles reflex","Sensory loss on the medial calf"],t.s)
B.aaZ=new A.bx("In an S1 radiculopathy, which finding is most expected?",B.a1C,2,"S1 radiculopathy classically presents with LOSS OF THE ACHILLES REFLEX and plantar flexion weakness.")
B.a_t=s([B.aaR,B.abe,B.aby,B.aaY,B.abp,B.aaV,B.ab9,B.ab5,B.abv,B.aaZ],t.hB)
B.abD=new A.lY(B.a_t,"Radiculopathy Mastery","Test your skills in root-level localization.",null)
B.acx=new A.Vl(null)
B.acy=new A.GC(null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null)
B.Ei=new A.aQ(1,1)
B.e6=new A.aQ(2,2)
B.acz=new A.aQ(3,3)
B.acA=new A.aQ(-1/0,-1/0)
B.acB=new A.aQ(1.5,1.5)
B.acC=new A.aQ(1/0,1/0)
B.acD=new A.aj(0,0)
B.acE=new A.aj(0,!0)
B.dI=new A.IQ(2,"collapsed")
B.acH=new A.aj(B.dI,B.dI)
B.acI=new A.aj("Far-field Potential","An electrical signal recorded at a massive distance from the generator. Because it is so far away, the voltage change hits all recording electrodes instantaneously at exactly the same time. The massive stimulus artifact is a far-field potential.")
B.acJ=new A.aj("Cathode","The active (black) pole of the stimulator where depolarization of the nerve actually begins. Must always be aimed toward recording electrodes.")
B.acQ=new A.aj("Amplitude","The height (mV) of the waveform, representing the total number of axons firing.")
B.acR=new A.aj("Near-field Potential","An electrical signal recorded by an electrode located very close to the biological generator (e.g., standard sensory or motor responses). The voltage changes dynamically as the signal moves.")
B.acS=new A.aj(B.O,0)
B.acT=new A.aj("Latency","The time (ms) from stimulus to the initial onset of the waveform.")
B.acV=new A.aj("Temporal Dispersion","The broadening of a waveform due to fibers conducting at different speeds, common in demyelination.")
B.acX=new A.aj("Phase Cancellation","In sensory studies, fast fibers arrive at the electrode early (creating an upward wave), and slower fibers arrive later (creating a downward wave). These opposite waves smash into each other and cancel each other out, artificially reducing the total amplitude the machine reads.")
B.l6=new A.IQ(0,"left")
B.l7=new A.IQ(1,"right")
B.acY=new A.aj(B.l6,B.l7)
B.kP=new A.dy(4,"scrollLeft")
B.kQ=new A.dy(8,"scrollRight")
B.ad_=new A.aj(B.kP,B.kQ)
B.ad0=new A.aj(B.kQ,B.kP)
B.ad1=new A.aj("Common Mode Rejection","A differential amplifier's brilliant ability to subtract out identical electrical noise (like 60Hz hum) present at both the Active and Reference electrodes, leaving only the biological nerve signal.")
B.ad2=new A.aj(!1,!1)
B.ad3=new A.aj(!1,null)
B.ad4=new A.aj(!1,!0)
B.kM=new A.dy(16,"scrollUp")
B.kN=new A.dy(32,"scrollDown")
B.ad7=new A.aj(B.kM,B.kN)
B.ad9=new A.aj("Anode",'The positive (red) pole. If placed between the cathode and recording electrodes, it can cause "anodal block".')
B.add=new A.aj(B.kN,B.kM)
B.adg=new A.aj("Volume Conduction","The passive spread of electrical current through bodily tissues and fluids, much like ripples in a pond. This allows muscles from far away to contaminate your recording.")
B.adh=new A.aj(!0,!1)
B.adi=new A.aj(!0,!0)
B.adj=new A.aj("H-Reflex","An electrical analog of the tendon monosynaptic reflex. Bypasses the muscle spindle.")
B.adk=new A.aj(B.l7,B.l6)
B.adl=new A.fy("Depolarization","+30mV",'Na+ floods into the cell, rapidly shifting the internal charge from negative to positive. This is the "all-or-none" action potential spike we record on the screen.')
B.adm=new A.fy("Hyperpolarization","Overshoot","The K+ channels are slightly slow to close, allowing too much positive charge to escape. The potential briefly drops below -70mV before the resting state is restored.")
B.adn=new A.fy("Resting State","-70mV","The nerve is negatively charged relative to the outside. This is actively maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase pump, which burns ATP to constantly push 3 Na+ ions out for every 2 K+ ions it pulls in. The nerve is a loaded spring, waiting to fire.")
B.ado=new A.fy("Repolarization","Restoring","The Na+ channels quickly snap shut (inactivation), and K+ channels open. K+ rushes out of the cell, dropping the internal charge back toward negative.")
B.adp=new A.fy("Threshold","-55mV","When a stimulus (either natural or from our stimulator) pushes the local charge from -70mV up to -55mV, an explosive chain reaction begins. Voltage-gated Na+ channels suddenly pop open.")
B.adq=new A.r1(["Group C","0.5-2 m/s","Tiny, Unmyelinated","Dull, aching, 'Slow' Pain, Warm temperature, and Autonomic functions (sweating, heart rate). The 'Dial-up Internet'."])
B.adr=new A.r1(["Group A-gamma (A\u03b3)","15-30 m/s","Medium Myelinated","Intrafusal Motor to muscle spindles (maintains muscle tone)."])
B.ads=new A.r1(["Group A-alpha (A\u03b1)","70-120 m/s","Massive, Heavily Myelinated","Extrafusal Motor driving (muscle contraction) and Proprioception. The 'High-Speed Internet' lines."])
B.adt=new A.r1(["Group A-delta (A\u03b4)","12-30 m/s","Small, Thinly Myelinated","Sharp, pricking, 'Fast' Pain and Cold temperature."])
B.adu=new A.r1(["Group A-beta (A\u03b2)","30-70 m/s","Large, Moderately Myelinated","Touch, Pressure, and Vibration. (These are the purely sensory fibers we test during a SNAP)."])
B.adv=new A.vY(["A-alpha","70-120 m/s","Massive","Motor contraction & Proprioception.",B.mq])
