a0=A.cd("Anterior Interosseous Nerve Syndrome",a2,s2,"CRITICAL (NCS is normal in pure AIN)",A.a([A.z(!1,"Spared (Not AIN-innervated)",f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,w7,"AIN",f0,"Absent/Severely Reduced",i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,"Flexor Digitorum Profundus 2","AIN",f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,w3,"AIN",f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!1,"Spared (Proximal to AIN)",f0,f0,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,f0,o9,f0)],n),"AIN syndrome is a pure motor neuropathy. The hallmark is the inability to flex the distal phalanges of the thumb (FPL) and index finger (FDP 2), resulting in a characteristic 'pincer' pinch instead of a round 'OK' sign. Because the AIN carries no cutaneous sensory fibers, the NCS is characteristically normal, making EMG of the AIN-innervated muscles (FPL, FDP 2, PQ) the definitive diagnostic tool.",a1,"ain",a3,ae7,ae6,!0,a0,A.a(["AIN syndrome (Kiloh-Nevin) involves only the motor branch of the median nerve supplying the FPL, FDP 2/3, and PQ.","Crucial Clinical Pearl: AIN syndrome has NO sensory loss. If the patient has numbness, look for PTS or CTS.","NCS studies (Median sensory and motor to APB) are characteristically NORMAL in AIN syndrome.","The diagnosis is made solely on EMG, showing denervation only in the AIN-innervated triad (FPL, FDP 2, PQ)."],af2),"Difficulty Making the 'OK' Sign")
