a1=A.cd(w8,a3,s2,"INDICATED (High-level localization)",A.a([A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,h4,o9,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,"Flexor Carpi Radialis (FCR)",h0,f0,h4,o9,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,w7,w4,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,s0,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0)],n),"This rare high-median entrapment occurs at the supracondylar process of the humerus, where the Ligament of Struthers compresses the median nerve. Unlike Pronator Teres Syndrome (which spares the PT branch), this lesion is PROXIMAL to the PT branch, causing weakness in the Pronator Teres, FCR, FPL, and APB. Diagnosis is supported by seeing a supracondylar process on X-ray.",a2,"struthers",a4,ae7,ae6,!0,a1,A.a(["Median neuropathy at the Ligament of Struthers is a high-arm entrapment near the supracondylar process.","Classic differentiator from PTS: The Pronator Teres is weak (in PTS, it is spared).","Classic differentiator from CTS: The Forearm muscles and Palm sensation are involved.","Radiographic hallmark: A bony supracondylar process on lateral/AP X-rays of the distal humerus."],af2),"Forearm Weakness with Mid-Arm Pain")
ae6=A.cc(48,"Inability to straighten fingers and thumb, but no numbness",i1,"Noticed difficulty 3 days ago. He can extend his wrist but it 'pulls' towards the thumb side. He cannot lift his fingers or thumb up from a flat surface. No history of trauma. No neck pain. No sensory symptoms at all.",x1,i2,"Osteoarthritis of the elbow")
ae7=A.cg("No visible atrophy (acute).","Deep tenderness over the proximal lateral forearm (over the supinator muscle).","Right Brachioradialis reflex 2+. Triceps reflex 2+. Left reflexes symmetric.",v3,"STRICTLY NORMAL throughout the radial, median, and ulnar distributions. No snuffbox numbness.","Negative 'OK' sign. Negative Tinel's at the wrist.","Right Finger Extension (EDC) 1/5, Thumb Extension (EPL) 1/5, Thumb Abduction (APL) 2/5. Wrist Extension: 4/5 (Presents with RADIAL deviation due to preserved ECRL/ECRB and weak ECU). Brachioradialis and Supinator strength: 5/5.")
a4=A.a([A.V(x2,d9),A.V("High Radial Neuropathy (Saturday Night Palsy)","A high radial lesion would involve the Brachioradialis and Supinator and ALWAYS cause sensory loss in the snuffbox/dorsal hand territory."),A.V(n4,"Radiculopathy would involve the triceps (root-level) and typically cause neck pain and sensory changes in the middle finger."),A.V("Lead Poisoning Neuropathy","Classically causes Bilateral wrist drop; this case is focal/unilateral and associated with local forearm pain."),A.V("Extensor Tendon Rupture","Common in Rheumatoid Arthritis; however, tendon rupture would not explain the radial deviation of the wrist or the neurogenic findings on EMG.")],ae8)
a2=A.a4(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Lateral elbow/forearm pain.","neurological","Finger/thumb weakness. NO SENSORY LOSS."],af0,af0)
a3=A.a(["None."],af2)
a3=A.ce(A.a(["Ultrasound Forearm: Compression of the radial nerve at the Arcade of Frohse (proximal border of supinator).","MRI Elbow: Synovitis of the radio-humeral joint potentially compressing the deep radial nerve."],af2),a3)
a5=A.a([A.ad(!1,f5,"Crucial finding ruling out high radial neuropathy",f3,f4,f6),A.ad(!1,i7,f0,e6,i6,i8),A.ad(!1,n7,f0,f1,g1,n8)],q)
a6=A.a([A.am(!0,l0,"Low amplitude CMAP from a PIN-innervated muscle",u7,v1,p2),A.am(!1,j4,f0,g6,f7,j5),A.am(!1,g2,f0,g1,g0,g3)],o)
a5=A.cf(A.a([A.db(!1,j7,f2,f4,g5,f0)],m),a6,a5)
a2=A.cd("Posterior Interosseous Nerve Syndrome",a4,s2,"CRITICAL (NCS is characteristically normal)",A.a([A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,s4,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,"Extensor Digitorum Communis (EDC)",x3,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,x4,x3,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!1,"Spared (Proximal to PIN)",f0,f0,f0,f0,u9,h9,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,"Spared (Innervated before/at entry to arcade)",f0,f0,f0,f0,"Supinator",h9,f0,f0,o9,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,o0,h9,f0,f0,"C6-C8",f0)],n),"PIN syndrome is a pure motor branch neuropathy of the radial nerve. The hallmark is 'finger drop' with preservation of the Brachioradialis and Supinator (which branch before the PIN enters the Arcade of Frohse). A characteristic finding is Radial Deviation during wrist extension, because the ECRL (Radio-radial) is spared while the ECU (PIN-radial) is weak. Like AIN, the Radial Sensory SNAP is strictly normal, as the PIN carries no cutaneous sensation.",a3,"pin",a5,ae7,ae6,!0,a2,A.a(["PIN syndrome is the radial equivalent of AIN\u2014a pure motor syndrome with strictly Normal Sensation.","Localization Pearl: Preservation of Brachioradialis and Radial Sensory SNAP localizes the lesion distal to the mid-arm/elbow bifurcation.","The 'Radial Deviation' of the wrist is a pathognomonic sign, caused by imbalance between the spared ECRL and the weak ECU.","The most common site of entrapment is the Arcade of Frohse in the supinator muscle."],af2),"Finger Drop without Numbness")
ae6=A.cc(29,"Complete' wrist drop' and numbness on the back of the hand after a long night of sleep",i1,"Woke up after a heavy night of drinking with his arm draped over a hard chair. He found he could not lift his wrist or fingers at all. Significant numbness on the back of the thumb and hand. No neck pain. No trauma.",i4,"Student",i4)
ae7=A.cg("Wrist and fingers hanging in a flexed position (Wrist Drop). No atrophy (hyperacute).","No significant tenderness in the neck or forearm.","Right Brachioradialis reflex 0. Triceps reflex 2+. Left reflexes symmetric.","Full passive ROM. Active extension zero.","Decreased sensation over the radial sensory territory (Snuffbox and dorsal first webspace).","Positive Tinel's sign at the spiral groove of the humerus; Negative Tinel's at the wrist/elbow.","Right Wrist Extension (ECRL/B, ECU) 0/5, Finger Extension (EDC) 0/5, Thumb Extension (EPL) 0/5. Brachioradialis 1/5. Supinator 2/5. Triceps strength 5/5. Normal hand intrinsics (APB, ADM, FDI).")
a5=A.a([A.V("Radial Neuropathy at the Spiral Groove (Saturday Night Palsy)",d9),A.V(x2,"PIN syndrome spares the Brachioradialis and Supinator and has STRICTLY NORMAL sensation. This case has both BR weakness and snuffbox numbness."),A.V(n4,"Radiculopathy would typically cause neck pain and involve the triceps; sensory loss would be in the middle finger rather than the first webspace."),A.V("Brachial Plexopathy (Posterior Cord)","A posterior cord lesion would involve the axillary nerve as well, leading to weak shoulder abduction (Deltoid), which is spared here."),A.V("Radial Neuropathy at the Axilla","An axillary-level radial lesion (e.g. 'Crutch Palsy') would involve the Triceps, which is spared in this mid-humeral spiral groove injury.")],ae8)
a3=A.a4(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","No joint pain.","neurological","Wrist drop and dorsal hand numbness."],af0,af0)
a4=A.a(["None."],af2)
a4=A.ce(A.a(["Ultrasound Humerus: Focal swelling of the radial nerve within the spiral groove.","MRI Arm: Normal; no structural mass or fracture."],af2),a4)
a6=A.a([A.ad(!0,k6,"Characteristic finding in high radial neuropathy",f3,s4,k6),A.ad(!1,i7,f0,e6,i6,i8),A.ad(!1,n7,f0,f1,g1,n8)],q)
a7=A.a([A.am(!1,i9,f0,e7,"Radial Motor (EIP) - Below Groove",p2),A.am(!0,"0.5","Profound conduction block and slowing across the spiral groove",w1,"Radial Motor (EIP) - Above Groove",f5),A.am(!1,j4,f0,g6,f7,j5),A.am(!1,g2,f0,g1,g0,g3)],o)
