a7=A.cd("Suprascapular Nerve Entrapment",a9,s2,"INDICATED (Levels of entrapment)",A.a([A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,u4,z1,f0,h4,v2,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,y3,z1,f0,h4,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,r8,z2,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,s0,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,z3,z4,f0,f0,z5,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,y4,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Suprascapular neuropathy at the **Suprascapular Notch** leads to weakness and atrophy of both the **Supraspinatus** and **Infraspinatus**. This is a purely motor/joint-pain syndrome (the nerve carries no cutaneous sensory fibers). A key localization pearl is **Deltoid sparing** (ruling out C5/Upper Trunk) and **Supraspinatus involvement** (ruling out the more distal Spinoglenoid notch site). In athletes, this is often caused by repetitive overhead motion or a paralabral cyst.",a8,"suprascapular",b0,ae7,ae6,!0,a7,A.a(["The suprascapular nerve supplies the supraspinatus and infraspinatus; it carries only motor and sensory fibers to the GH and AC joints.","Localization Site 1: **Suprascapular Notch** (involves both muscles).","Localization Site 2: **Spinoglenoid Notch** (involves ONLY the infraspinatus).","Athletes (volleyball, baseball) and patients with paralabral cysts are at highest risk.","Normal Deltoid and Biceps EMG is critical to rule out C5 radiculopathy or Upper Trunk plexopathy."],af2),"Deep Shoulder Pain and External Rotation Weakness")
ae6=A.cc(58,"Inability to lift the right arm after a shoulder dislocation",d5,"Tripped and fell 3 weeks ago, sustaining an anterior shoulder dislocation which was reduced in the ED. Since then, she has been unable to lift her arm to the side. Numbness noted over a small area on the outer shoulder. No neck pain. No weakness in the hand or elbow.","Calcium, Vitamin D",z6,"Osteoporosis")
ae7=A.cg("Noticeable flattening of the right deltoid muscle. No other visible atrophy.","Mild residual soreness in the glenohumeral joint. No bony abnormalities palpable.",z7,"Full passive ROM. Active abduction capped at 20-30 degrees due to weakness.","Decreased sensation over the lateral aspect of the upper arm ('Regimental Patch' area). Normal sensation in the forearm and hand.","Negative Empty Can (for pain). Negative Spurling's maneuver.","Right Shoulder Abduction (Deltoid) 1/5. External Rotation (Infraspinatus) 5/5. Biceps 5/5. Triceps 5/5. Hand intrinsics 5/5.")
b0=A.a([A.V("Axillary Neuropathy (Shoulder Dislocation)",d9),A.V(u0,"Radiculopathy would typically involve the Biceps (Musculocutaneous) and Supraspinatus (Suprascapular), and often presents with neck pain and paraspinal involvement. Here, muscle weakness is isolated to the deltoid."),A.V(y5,"Would involve a combination of C5-C6 muscles (Biceps, BR, Deltoid, Infraspinatus) and cause sensory loss in the lateral forearm. Here, only the deltoid and its sensory patch are involved."),A.V("Rotator Cuff Tear (Full Thickness)","A massive tear can cause pseudo-paralysis of abduction, but it would NOT cause the 'regimental patch' sensory loss or the neurogenic findings on EMG."),A.V(u2,"Involves Supraspinatus/Infraspinatus; this case has preserved external rotation (IS) and weak abduction (Deltoid).")],ae8)
