a8=A.cd(u1,b0,k0,"INDICATED (Prognostication and localization)",A.a([A.z(!0,f0,f0,q5,f0,f0,"Deltoid (Ant/Mid)",z2,f0,t5,v2,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,"Teres Minor",z2,f0,h4,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,s0,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,y3,z1,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,z3,z4,f0,f0,z5,f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.z(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,y4,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Axillary nerve injury is a well-known complication of anterior shoulder dislocations. Localization is confirmed by **isolated weakness of the Deltoid**, **sensory loss in the regimental patch distribution**, and **sparing of all other C5-C6 muscles** (Biceps, Infraspinatus, Supraspinatus). EMG shows denervation in the deltoid while proximal (Suprascapular) and other distal C5-C6 branches remain normal.",a9,"axillary",b1,ae7,ae6,!0,a8,A.a(["The axillary nerve is highly vulnerable in shoulder dislocations as it winds around the surgical neck of the humerus.","Localization Pearl: Isolated Deltoid weakness with **Sparing of the Infraspinatus/Biceps** and **Normal LABC SNAP** rules out radiculopathy and upper trunk plexopathy.","The 'Regimental Patch' is the sensory territory of the superior lateral cutaneous nerve of the arm (branch of axillary).","EMG is essential to rule out co-existing rotator cuff tears which may clinically mimic nerve weakness."],af2),"Shoulder Weakness after a Fall")
ae6=A.cc(28,"Pain in the shoulder and difficulty with overhead reaching; noticed a 'bulge' in her back",d5,"Professional swimmer who developed aching shoulder pain after a grueling training block. Noticed her right shoulder blade 'sticks out' when she pushes against a wall. No numbness in the hand or arm. Denies recent trauma.",x1,"Swimmer",i4)
ae7=A.cg("Obvious winging of the medial border of the right scapula, especially when the patient pushes against a wall (protraction).","Mild tenderness over the right serratus anterior muscle.",z7,"Full active and passive ROM of the glenohumeral joint, but scapulothoracic rhythm is disrupted.","STRICTLY NORMAL throughout the arm and shoulder.","Positive Scapular Winging Test (with wall push).","Right Shoulder Flexion/Abduction 4/5 (limited by unstable scapula). Serratus Anterior 2/5. Rhomboids 5/5. Trapezius 5/5. Biceps/Triceps 5/5. Hand intrinsics 5/5.")
b1=A.a([A.V("Long Thoracic Neuropathy (Winged Scapula)",d9),A.V("Spinal Accessory Neuropathy (CN XI)","CN XI injury would cause winging of the **lateral** border of the scapula (Trapezius weakness) and weakness in shoulder shrugging; here the medial border is winged and shrug is normal."),A.V("Dorsal Scapular Neuropathy","Would cause weakness of the Rhomboids and Levator Scapulae, with the scapula shifting **laterally** at rest; here the scapula reflects medial winging during protraction."),A.V(y2,"Would involve multiple muscles (Biceps, Deltoid, Supraspinatus) and cause sensory loss. This case is isolated to the serratus anterior."),A.V("Facio-Scapulo-Humeral Dystrophy (FSHD)","Can cause scapular winging but is usually bilateral, chronic, and involves the face (orbicularis oculi weakness) which is absent here.")],ae8)
a9=A.a4(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Shoulder pain and difficulty reaching high shelves.","neurological","Scapular winging. **NO SENSORY LOSS**."],af0,af0)
