c9=A.cd("Right Lower Trunk Brachial Plexopathy (Klumpke's Palsy)",d1,s2,e2,A.a([A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.z(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,j9,h6,f0,h4,"C8",f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,s0,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.z(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,r8,z2,f0,f0,"C5",f0),A.z(!1,"Confirms post-ganglionic",f0,f0,f0,f0,"C8-T1 Paraspinals",f0,f0,f0,f0,k6)],n),"Acute traction injury (upward pull) causing damage to the lower trunk (C8-T1). Localization is confirmed by: 1) Abnormal MAC and Ulnar SNAPs (post-ganglionic), 2) Weakness in all C8-T1 innervated muscles (Median, Ulnar, and Radial), and 3) Sparing of proximal (C5-C7) muscles and reflexes.",d0,"klumpke",d2,ae7,ae6,!0,c9,A.a(["Klumpke's palsy results from injury to the lower trunk (C8-T1), often due to hyperabduction of the arm.","The hallmark finding for localization is the abnormal Medial Antebrachial Cutaneous (MAC) SNAP, which distinguishes it from a C8 radiculopathy.","Physical exam classically shows a 'claw hand' due to weakness of the lumbricals and interossei.","Normal paraspinals and SNAPs would suggest a root level lesion (radiculopathy), while abnormal SNAPs and normal paraspinals confirm a plexopathy."],af2),"Weak Hand and Medial Arm Numbness")
ae6=A.cc(58,"Burning pain and numbness along the inner aspect of the right leg following knee replacement surgery",d5,"58-year-old female who underwent an uncomplicated total knee arthroplasty (TKA) 6 weeks ago. Since the surgery, she has had persistent burning pain and numbness on the medial side of her leg, extending from the knee down towards the medial ankle. No weakness noted. No back pain.","Gabapentin, Acetaminophen",z6,"Osteoarthritis of the knees")
ae7=A.cg("Well-healed surgical incision on the anterior knee. No muscle atrophy in the quadriceps.","Tenderness along the medial joint line and infrapatellar region.","2+ and symmetric patellar and Achilles reflexes.","Full ROM at the hip. Knee ROM 0-110 degrees, limited by post-surgical stiffness but not weakness.","Decreased pinprick and light touch along the medial leg below the knee (Saphenous distribution). Sensation on the thigh and lateral leg is normal.","Negative straight leg raise. Negative femoral stretch test.","5/5 strength in hip flexion (Iliopsoas), knee extension (Quadriceps), and hip adduction (Adductors).")
ae8=A.a([A.V("Isolated Saphenous Neuropathy",d9),A.V(x7,"Femoral neuropathy would involve weakness in the quadriceps and a diminished patellar reflex; here both are normal."),A.V("L3 or L4 Radiculopathy","Radiculopathy would typically involve quadriceps weakness and paraspinal denervation; also, the Saphenous SNAP would be preserved in a pre-ganglionic root lesion."),A.V("Infrapatellar Branch of Saphenous Injury","This is a subset of saphenous injury, but here the sensory loss extends further down the medial leg, suggesting a lesion to the main saphenous trunk.")],ae8)
d2=A.a4(["constitutional",u6,"musculoskeletal","Medial leg pain. No hip or back pain.","neurological","Purely sensory symptoms in the medial leg. No weakness."],af0,af0)
